data.body:
Similar to issue #332, if you try to draw the stage to a scaled `BitmapData`, any objects with `clipRects` won't get drawn properly.

I'm using this code to capture the stage (modified from `drawToBitmapData()` to allow for transparent bg of different colours and scaling):

```
public function screenshot( scale:Number = 1.0, bgColour:uint = 0xffffff, bgAlpha:Number = 1.0 ):BitmapData
{
    // get the stage
    var stage:Stage     = Starling.current.stage;
    var w:Number        = stage.stageWidth;
    var h:Number        = stage.stageHeight;
    var c:Colour        = Colour.fromHexi( bgColour ); // Colour is a simple support class to make working with colours easier
    c.alpha             = bgAlpha;
    var bmd:BitmapData  = new BitmapData( w * scale, h * scale, ( c.alpha < 1.0 ), 0x00000000 );

    // create our render support
    var rs:RenderSupport    = new RenderSupport;
    rs.renderTarget         = null;
    if( scale != 1.0 )
        rs.scaleMatrix( scale, scale );
    rs.setOrthographicProjection( 0, 0, w, h );

    // clear the support to our desired colour (NOTE: seems to want pre-multiplied alpha)
    c.premultiplyAlpha();
    rs.clear( c.rgb );

    // render the stage
    stage.render( rs, 1.0 );
    rs.finishQuadBatch();

    // render to our BitmapData
    Starling.current.context.drawToBitmapData( bmd );
    Starling.current.context.present(); // required on some platforms to avoid flickering
    return bmd;
}
```

To try and get around the `clipRect` problem, I originally tried to copy all the stage objects into a `Sprite`, `flatten()` it, draw, then recopy them back to the stage. That essentially just removed the `clipRect` altogether; not very useful, as the `clipRect`` was there for a purpose :)

It's possible to get a scaled screenshot, by drawing it full size first, then drawing that _that_ `BitmapData` to another one, with the proper scale. While this works, it's not an ideal use of memory.

I looked a bit closer at what was actually drawn when capturing the screen with `clipRect` objects in it, and it's not that they weren't showing, but it seemed more like the final coordinates weren't calculated properly (I guess because it uses something like `GL_SCISSOR_RECT` in the background which works in screen coords?)

I went into `starling.display.Sprite` and changed (line 134):

```
public function getClipRect(targetSpace:DisplayObject, resultRect:Rectangle=null):Rectangle
```

to

```
public function getClipRect(targetSpace:DisplayObject, resultRect:Rectangle=null, support:RenderSupport=null):Rectangle
```

line 144 from:

```
var transMatrix:Matrix = getTransformationMatrix(targetSpace, sHelperMatrix);
```

to

```
var transMatrix:Matrix = (support != null) ? support.modelViewMatrix : getTransformationMatrix(targetSpace, sHelperMatrix);
```

and line 194 from:

```
var clipRect:Rectangle = support.pushClipRect(getClipRect(stage, sHelperRect));
```

to

```
var clipRect:Rectangle = support.pushClipRect(getClipRect(stage, sHelperRect, support));
```

This will correctly draw the object at scale, with the `clipRect` in the right place, though I don't know enough about the Starling internals to know what other sort of impact this will have. So far I haven't noticed anything amiss, but then my tests aren't exactly exhaustive

Now that Starling handles rotated items inside an atlas, is it possible to add a public function to know if a specific item is rotated or not inside the atlas?

For exemple, adding this to the [TextureAtlas class](https://github.com/PrimaryFeather/Starling-Framework/blob/master/starling/src/starling/textures/TextureAtlas.as):

```
/** Returns the rotation associated with a specific name. */
public function getRotation(name:String):Boolean
{
    var info:TextureInfo = mTextureInfos[name];
    return info ? info.rotated : null;
}
```

[Fault] exception, information=Error: Error #3694: The object was disposed by an earlier call of dispose() on it.

Starling.handleLostContext is true.

Using the following code, click the button to trigger this error:

```
var button:Button = new Button(Texture.fromColor(100, 40, 0xffff00ff));
button.text = "Click Me";
button.addEventListener(Event.TRIGGERED, function():void
{
    if(Starling.current.nativeStage.displayState != StageDisplayState.NORMAL)
    {
        Starling.current.nativeStage.displayState = StageDisplayState.NORMAL
    }
    else
    {
        Starling.current.nativeStage.displayState = StageDisplayState.FULL_SCREEN_INTERACTIVE;
    }
})
this.addChild(button);
```

The transformation matrix setter computes the scaleX/scaleY values wrong

Example: 
mScaleX = matrix.a / Math.cos(mSkewY);
mScaleY = matrix.d / Math.cos(mSkewX);

If we have a rotation matrix that is 90 a and d are both 0. Leading to a scale that is 0 and to a non displayed object.
